Dear Jill,

Thanks a lot for finding all of this out. I hadn't previously done much research into Cholera data - Majid mentioned it earlier this week as something that Yvonne is keen for us to look at - so the paper is helpful.

It seems the authors were able to get hold of weekly/monthly data from the start of 2011 from the DHIMS2 internet-based reporting system, and that this includes the incidence of Cholera. From my point of view this would be ideal. I don't know the latency, but weekly/monthly data from 2011-2018/19 this would be great, and definitely something we could work with. In terms of spatial coverage I think I would focus on GAMA.

As Brian alluded to, the initial idea would be to look at the correspondence between Cholera and flooding. Assuming the data shows a link, something interesting to look at would be the extent and type of flooding which results in an increase in Cholera, and how this varies across Accra. Ideally, therefore, the spatial resolution would be higher than the district level. I guess this might be contained in the DHIMS2 system.

I hope this helps. Thanks again for following it up.

Cheers,
Simon

